The importance of washing hands for human health, especially for people in vulnerable circumstances, such as mothers who have just given birth or soldiers to hospitals, was first recognized by two pioneers in the middle of the 20th century: Hungarian doctor Ignaz Semmelweis, who worked in Vienna, Austria, and Florence Nightingale, English, the "founder of modern nursing".
