The severe acute respiratory syndrome 2 (SARS-CoV-2) is a new severe acute respiratory syndrome coronary virus, which was isolated for the first time by three people with pneumonia connected to an acute respiratory disease group in Wuhan.
All features of the new SARS-CoV-2 virus are found in related nature-related coronaviruses.
Outside of the human body, the domestic soap kills the virus, as it returns its protective bubble. SARS-CoV-2 is closely related to the original SARS-CoV.
The lungs are the most affected organs of the COVID-19, because the virus enters the host cells by converting angiotensin type I 2 enzyme (ECA2), which is more abundant in the type II alveolar cells of the lungs.
The virus uses a special surface glycoprotein called "spicula" (peplomer) to connect with ECA2 and enter the host cell.
In 12% of the infected people hospitalized in Wuhan, China, acute cardiac injury was identified, which is more frequent in serious illness.
Cardiovascular symptoms are high due to systemic inflammatory response and immune system disorders during disease development, but acute myocardial injury may be associated with heart ECA2 receptors.
ECA2 receptors have a high expression in the heart and participate in its operation.
A high incidence of thrombosis (31%) and venous thromboembolism (25%) was detected in patients with COVID-19 virus infections and may be associated with a prognosis. In the autopsys of people who died from COVID-19, diffuse alveolar damage (ADD) and inflammatory infiltrates with lymphocytes in the lungs were detected.
Although SARS-COV-2 has tropics for epithelial cells expressing ECA2 from respiratory pathways, patients with COVID-19 severe have symptoms of systemic hyperinflammation.
In particular, it was observed that GM-CSF pathogen secretaries T were associated with the recruitment of IL-6 secretors and a severe pulmonary pathology in patients with COVID-19.
In autopsies, lymphocyte infiltrates were also reported.
WHO has published several test protocols to detect the disease.
The standard test method is the polymerase chain reaction with inverse real-time transcription (rRT-PCR).
The test is usually performed in samples of the respiratory pathways obtained by a nasopharyngeal hisopate; however, samples of nasal or spouty hisopate may also be used.
